pouch boundary-line patch 0025 - CL-1b-0 populate environ from /env.

The Clade arc (docs/LLVM-DESIGN.md) sub-chunk CL-1b-0. The kernel writes
envp[0] = NULL for every program ("no envp at v1.0", exec.h): `environ` is
empty in every pouch process. Thylacine's environment instead lives in the
per-Proc /env device (the Plan 9 Egrp idiom -- a variable is the file
/env/NAME, inherited by children via the kernel clone env_clone_into). CL-0's
census (LLVM-DESIGN.md section 16.2) confirmed this crt boundary line is
required: clang/lld read PATH/TMPDIR/etc. via getenv, and a spawned cc1/lld
inherits its parent's /env through the rfork clone.

This adds a crt hook that reads /env once at startup into a malloc'd
"NAME=value" vector and points __environ at it, so getenv() AND environ
iteration both work. It runs from __libc_start_main right after __init_libc
(malloc + TLS up) and before the ctors (so a constructor's getenv sees a
populated environ). Fail-soft: a missing/empty /env leaves __environ as the
kernel's empty envp -- today's behaviour, never a crash.

/env stays the source of truth. A later setenv mutates only this in-process
copy; writing a change back to /env (and the posix_spawn envp arg, which the
SYS_SPAWN_FULL_ARGV _pad_envp slot reserves) are v1.x kernel-surface lifts.

Files:
  src/env/_pouch_env.c          NEW -- __pouch_env_init(): readdir /env,
                                open+read each NAME, build __environ.
  src/env/__libc_start_main.c   call __pouch_env_init() after __init_libc.

